claims.text: I can feel tightness in my shoulders.
It feels like a weight pressing on me.
The heaviness seems to come from my work stress.
My friend's advice helps a bit.
My breath feels stuck around my chest area.
Work stress is creating a barrier.
My shoulders carry the weight of every deadline, every meeting with my boss, Sarah.
When I think about Sarah's expectations, my shoulders just clench up automatically.
When I think about tomorrow's presentation to Sarah and the board, my shoulders just tense up again.
Marcus always tells me to drop my shoulders when we're walking together.
The work stress with Sarah and the deadlines just builds up in my shoulders again.
It's like a cycle.
Understanding this pattern between my shoulders and work stress is already helping.
Alex believes their body is an accurate barometer of work-related anxiety
Dr. Wilson assumes that exploring the bodily tension will reveal deeper emotional or relational issues
The therapeutic process is expected to reduce Alex’s work stress by making the body-mind connection explicit
Alex implicitly views Sarah (the boss) as an oppressive authority whose expectations are physically burdensome
Marcus’s casual reminders are framed as more immediately effective than formal therapy, implying a preference for peer support over clinical intervention
Somatic techniques are considered sufficient to address what may also be systemic workplace stressors
Tense. I can feel tightness in my shoulders.
I wish I could let go of this heaviness, but...
My friend's advice helps a bit, and I try to give myself some compassion.
My breath feels stuck... like the work stress is creating a barrier.
When I think about Sarah's expectations, my shoulders just clench up automatically.
Put me down! I'm tired of carrying this burden!
Marcus sounds like a caring friend... Helpful.
Thank you... I feel like understanding this pattern... is already helping.
